### PHP explode and implode

`explode()` splits a string into an array. `implode()` joins array elements into a string.

### explode

```php
<?php
$str = "apple,banana,orange,grape";
$fruits = explode(",", $str);
print_r($fruits);
// Array ( [0] => apple [1] => banana [2] => orange [3] => grape )

// Limit parameter
$limited = explode(",", $str, 2);
print_r($limited);
// Array ( [0] => apple [1] => banana,orange,grape )
?>
```

### implode (alias: join)

```php
<?php
$fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange"];
echo implode(", ", $fruits);
// apple, banana, orange

echo join(" | ", $fruits);
// apple | banana | orange

// Join with empty string
$chars = ["H", "e", "l", "l", "o"];
echo implode("", $chars); // Hello
?>
```

### Common Use Cases

| Task | Code |
|------|------|
| CSV parsing | `explode(",", $line)` |
| Path segments | `explode("/", $path)` |
| Query string | `explode("&", $queryString)` |
| SQL IN clause | `implode("','", $items)` |
| Tag list | `implode(", ", $tags)` |

> **Key Point:** `explode()` returns an array. `implode()` returns a string. The `join()` alias is interchangeable with `implode()`.
